What happens when you initialize a repository? Why do you need to do it?
You need to do it in order to create it.

How is the staging area different from the working directory and the repository? What value do you think it offers?
The stating area is the place where do you place files that you want in the repository. The value is that you can
choose wich files goes tracked by git.

How can you use the staging area to make sure you have one commit per logical change?
You can use git diff and git diff -stage to compare the changes you are going to commit.

What are some situations when branches would be helpful in keeping your history organized? How would branches help?
When you can add experimental feature to the program for example, branches help because you can move things around
without fearing breaking the project.

How do the diagrams help you visualize the branch structure?
It allows you to see the different history of the branches.

What is the result of merging two branches together? Why do we represent it in the diagram the way we do?
You create a commit that includes the changes made in bot branches, we represent it like that because now we have
only a branch, normally the master.

What are the pros and cons of Git's automatic merging vs. always doing merges manually?
Well it save time when there are no obvius conflicts.